snippet.textDisplay: You know what I think? Current research done by the Primate Research Institute in Japan revealed that our most closest relatives, the chimpanzees, have incredible temporal memory... well beyond human kind of stuff, or at least something you would expect from a super genius. The current hypothesis is that we traded some of our cognitive ability for the our ability of language; they kept their super memory, we have our complex languages. I wonder if something similar is the case with the tridactyls. Maybe their limited language ability, despite being the wisest and oldest, is a result of a trade between the ability to make complex languages and their natural ability to control the force. Maybe their chimpanzee counterparts are all shakespearean polyglots, able to learn any language in a matter of weeks.

Moreover "Natural Selection" has been noted as one of the weakest influences on evolution. Nearly all evolution has been Artificial Selection, as in other organisms determining the evolution of other organisms.

snippet.textDisplay:
I have a question for the film theorists.
What are some possible gasses Shrek and Fiona could breathe?
It may sound silly, but truth is, it's actually a pretty complex scientific question. In one scene they turned a frog and a snake into balloons by breathing into them, which suggests multiple things.
- Whatever they breathe out must be lighter than what they breathe in
- The metabolic reaction needs to be able to operate around body temperature, since Shrek and Fiona don't cook stuff by touching
- The metabolic reaction needs to be exothermic, needs to release energy and must not be too energy demanding, because otherwise it would be unsustainable for animals
It also kind of complicates matters that we don't know the air structure, atmospheric pressure, the magnetic field and gravitational forces. The only thing we know is, the sky is blue. We can deduce from it that there are no particles visible by eye in the air of Shrekaniverse, but... That's where I'm stuck.
